0{"DateTime":"2023-12-20T16:49:42.0049394Z","Version":0,"CopilotSessionId":{"Guid":"4095fa6a-a267-47b7-b57a-2cef9374c6fd","ClientId":{"Id":"Microsoft.VisualStudio.Conversations.Chat.HelpWindow"}},"Request":{"Prompt":"how do I enable verbose output from my dotnet run command so I can see what exactly the kestrel error is when I hit /user/signup","Context":{"VisibleDocuments":[],"PreSelectedSkill":null,"CorrelationId":{"Guid":"00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000000"}}},"Response":{"Content":"To enable verbose output from your \u0060dotnet run\u0060 command, you can use the \u0060--verbosity\u0060 option followed by the \u0060detailed\u0060 or \u0060diagnostic\u0060 level. This will provide you with a detailed log of the build process, which can help you identify any issues.\n\nHere\u0027s how you can do it:\n\n\u0060\u0060\u0060bash\ndotnet run --verbosity detailed\n\u0060\u0060\u0060\n\nor\n\n\u0060\u0060\u0060bash\ndotnet run --verbosity diagnostic\n\u0060\u0060\u0060\n\nThis will output a lot of information to your console, so you might want to redirect the output to a file for easier reading:\n\n\u0060\u0060\u0060bash\ndotnet run --verbosity detailed \u003E output.txt\n\u0060\u0060\u0060\n\nor\n\n\u0060\u0060\u0060bash\ndotnet run --verbosity diagnostic \u003E output.txt\n\u0060\u0060\u0060\n\nThen, you can open \u0060output.txt\u0060 in a text editor to inspect the output at your leisure.\n\nIf you\u0027re specifically interested in Kestrel errors, you might want to consider enabling logging in your ASP.NET Core application. You can do this by modifying your \u0060Program.cs\u0060 file to configure the logging level for Kestrel:\n\n\u0060\u0060\u0060csharp\npublic static IHostBuilder CreateHostBuilder(string[] args) =\u003E\n    Host.CreateDefaultBuilder(args)\n        .ConfigureWebHostDefaults(webBuilder =\u003E\n        {\n            webBuilder.UseStartup\u003CStartup\u003E();\n        })\n        .ConfigureLogging(logging =\u003E\n        {\n            logging.ClearProviders();\n            logging.AddConsole();\n            logging.AddDebug();\n            logging.AddFilter(\u0022Microsoft.AspNetCore.Server.Kestrel\u0022, LogLevel.Trace);\n        });\n\u0060\u0060\u0060\n\nThis will output Kestrel logs to the console when you run your application. You can adjust the \u0060LogLevel\u0060 as needed to control the verbosity of the logs.","Type":0,"Status":1,"FollowUpPrompts":["Explain the different log levels in .NET","How can I filter logs by category?"]},"SelectedFunctionName":"Explain","LoggedSkillInvocations":null,"ThreadName":null}
0{"DateTime":"2023-12-20T16:49:42.0049394Z","Version":0,"CopilotSessionId":{"Guid":"4095fa6a-a267-47b7-b57a-2cef9374c6fd","ClientId":{"Id":"Microsoft.VisualStudio.Conversations.Chat.HelpWindow"}},"Request":{"Prompt":"Here is my #file:KopkeHome-WebApp\\\\Program.cs for context","Context":{"VisibleDocuments":[],"PreSelectedSkill":null,"CorrelationId":{"Guid":"00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000000"}}},"Response":{"Content":"The \u0060Program.cs\u0060 file you\u0027ve provided is the entry point for your ASP.NET Core application. It\u0027s responsible for setting up the application and the HTTP pipeline.\n\nHere\u0027s a brief overview of what your \u0060Program.cs\u0060 file is doing:\n\n1. It creates a \u0060WebApplication\u0060 builder with the command-line arguments passed to the application.\n\n2. It sets up Serilog as the logging provider. Serilog is a third-party, open-source library that provides diagnostic logging to files, the console, and elsewhere.\n\n3. It adds various services to the application\u0027s dependency injection container, such as CORS, controllers with views, HTTP context accessor, AutoMapper, and an email service.\n\n4. It configures localization options, specifying that the application\u0027s resources are located in a \u0022Resources\u0022 folder and that the application supports English (US) and Spanish cultures.\n\n5. It adds session support to the application, with a session timeout of 30 minutes.\n\n6. It builds the application and configures the HTTP request pipeline. This includes setting up exception handling, CORS, HTTPS redirection, static files, request localization, routing, session, authorization, and a default route.\n\nIf you\u0027re encountering issues or have specific questions about this file, feel free to ask!","Type":0,"Status":1,"FollowUpPrompts":["Can you explain more about CORS?","How does session management work in ASP.NET Core?","Can you explain more about localization in ASP.NET Core?","How does Serilog work in ASP.NET Core?"]},"SelectedFunctionName":"Explain","LoggedSkillInvocations":null,"ThreadName":null}
0{"DateTime":"2023-12-20T16:49:42.0049394Z","Version":0,"CopilotSessionId":{"Guid":"4095fa6a-a267-47b7-b57a-2cef9374c6fd","ClientId":{"Id":"Microsoft.VisualStudio.Conversations.Chat.HelpWindow"}},"Request":{"Prompt":"how do I add verbose logging to requests that come in?","Context":{"VisibleDocuments":[],"PreSelectedSkill":null,"CorrelationId":{"Guid":"00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000000"}}},"Response":{"Content":"\u0060\u0060\u0060csharp\nusing Microsoft.AspNetCore.Hosting;\nusing Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting;\nusing Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;\n\npublic class Program\n{\n    public static void Main(string[] args)\n    {\n        CreateHostBuilder(args).Build().Run();\n    }\n\n    public static IHostBuilder CreateHostBuilder(string[] args) =\u003E\n        Host.CreateDefaultBuilder(args)\n            .ConfigureWebHostDefaults(webBuilder =\u003E\n            {\n                webBuilder.UseStartup\u003CStartup\u003E();\n            })\n            .ConfigureLogging(logging =\u003E\n            {\n                logging.ClearProviders();\n                logging.AddConsole();\n                logging.AddDebug();\n                logging.AddFilter(\u0022Microsoft.AspNetCore\u0022, LogLevel.Debug);\n                logging.AddFilter(\u0022System\u0022, LogLevel.Debug);\n                logging.AddFilter(\u0022Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore.Database.Command\u0022, LogLevel.Information);\n            });\n}\n\u0060\u0060\u0060","Type":1,"Status":1,"FollowUpPrompts":null},"SelectedFunctionName":"Modify","LoggedSkillInvocations":null,"ThreadName":null}
0{"DateTime":"2023-12-20T16:49:42.0049394Z","Version":0,"CopilotSessionId":{"Guid":"4095fa6a-a267-47b7-b57a-2cef9374c6fd","ClientId":{"Id":"Microsoft.VisualStudio.Conversations.Chat.HelpWindow"}},"Request":{"Prompt":"And where does that get logged to?  The terminal during \u0060dotnet run?\u0060","Context":{"VisibleDocuments":[],"PreSelectedSkill":null,"CorrelationId":{"Guid":"00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000000"}}},"Response":{"Content":"Yes, the logs will be output to the terminal when you run your application using \u0060dotnet run\u0060. The \u0060AddConsole()\u0060 method in the logging configuration ensures that log messages are written to the console.\n\nHowever, keep in mind that the visibility of these logs depends on the log level that has been set. In the provided code, the log level is set to \u0060Debug\u0060 for \u0060Microsoft.AspNetCore\u0060 and \u0060System\u0060, and \u0060Information\u0060 for \u0060Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore.Database.Command\u0060. This means that only log messages with these levels (or higher) will be displayed.\n\nIf you want to keep a persistent record of the logs, you might want to consider adding a file logger, or using a logging provider that supports log aggregation and storage.","Type":0,"Status":1,"FollowUpPrompts":["How can I add a file logger?","What is a logging provider that supports log aggregation and storage?"]},"SelectedFunctionName":"Explain","LoggedSkillInvocations":null,"ThreadName":null}
